document.masterDocTitle: A review of the Australian species of Ecnomina Kimmins and Daternomina Neboiss (Trichoptera: Ecnomidae)

mods:titleInfo.mods:title: A review of the Australian species of Ecnomina Kimmins and Daternomina Neboiss (Trichoptera: Ecnomidae)

subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis.
Daternomina birrarung
is distinguished from other species in the genus by having the superior appendages in lateral view branched, the ventral branch being strong.

Description. Head, body and wings brown; wings similar to
D. irrorata
( Fig. 1 ). Forewing length about 3.1 times width: male 4.4–5.2 mm , female 5.8 mm . Forewing fork 2 relatively long, sessile, about 1.5–1.9 times length of fork 3, nygma present; fork 3 relatively long, length about 1.8–3.2 times length footstalk, footstalk length about 1.5–2.1 times length cross-vein m; r-m and m displaced at fork 3 by about 1.6–1.9 times length cross-vein m; fork 4 length similar to fork 3; fork 5 long, about 1.8 times length of fork 4. Hindwing length about 3 times width; fork 2 sessile, length about 1.7–2.0 times length of fork 3.

Etymology. Birrarung - Victorian Aboriginal word for the Yarra River ( type locality).

Remarks.
Daternomina birrarung
has been collected widely from the eastern half of Victoria and eastern New South Wales (latitudinal range 29°50'- 38°55'S ).
